Abstract = {{Acid mine drainage (AMD) remains one of the major environmental problems
   for the mining industry. When AMD is produced on a mine site, passive
   treatment techniques such as limestone drains (LDs) can be used to
   improve water quality, particularly when the effluent is relatively
   small. In 1999, LDs were installed in combination with a cover with
   capillary barrier effects to rehabilitate the abandoned acid-generating
   Lorraine mine site in Quebec, Canada. However, the quality of the water
   exiting the LD does not meet the local regulations (even if a
   significant improvement has been observed). To better understand the
   behaviour of the drains, the hydraulic residence time (HRT) was
   evaluated using various tracer tests. Tests' results indicate that the
   HRT in the Lorraine LDs is close to the minimum value targeted at the
   design stage but is significantly different than those estimated from
   the geometrical characteristics and porosity of the drains and the water
   flow discharge.}},
