Pages = {{245-265}},
Abstract = {{This article studies differences in the results of using different risk
   estimation tools in the same hazardous situations involving dangerous
   machinery. We investigated how (a) types of risk estimation parameters
   and methods of constructing tools, (b) the number of levels of each
   parameter, and (c) the number of risk levels influence the results.
   Consequently, 31 risk estimation tools were compared by using them to
   estimate risk levels associated with 20 hazardous situations. Risk
   estimation appears to be tool-dependent, as different tools give
   different results with identical hazardous situations. The scope of the
   tool, its use, and construction could explain these differences. This
   article also proposes a series of rules for constructing tools to
   alleviate many problems associated with the variability of risk
