Abstract = {{The seismic performance of steel braced frames with bracing members
   intersecting columns between ground and roof levels in tall
   single-storey steel buildings is examined. Dividing the storey height in
   multiple X-bracing panels permits to reduce the length of the bracing
   elements, so that smaller brace sections can be selected while meeting
   the brace strength requirements and overall slenderness limits imposed
   by codes. Push-over analysis was performed to assess the performance of
   these frames. The influence of the relative height of the bracing
   panels, the presence of an intermediate strut, and the bending moment
   used for the design of the columns is studied. The numerical analyses
   showed that all these parameters may affect the amplitude and vertical
   distribution of brace buckling and yielding in the frame. Uneven
   distribution of inelastic response, with in-plane bending moment demand,
