Abstract = {{Steel braced frames that are designed to rock on their foundations have
   been proposed as an efficient way to resist seismic loads without
   structural damage or residual deformations. Although such systems have
   been shown to exhibit a desirable self-centering response, there have
   been concerns that higher mode effects cause excessive amplification of
   member design forces. To mitigate these effects, multiple structural
   fuses are proposed. This paper presents shake table test results from an
   eight-storey rocking steel frame that was tested at 30\% scale. The
   frame was designed to be able to rock at the base only, or also at
   midheight. In addition, the first-storey brace was designed to be
   replaced with a Self-Centering Energy-Dissipating (SCED) brace. Both of
   these secondary fuses were effective in reducing the shear and bending
   moment envelopes for the frame with only minor increases in the peak
   structural displacements.}},
