   Photon Innovat; CMC Microsystems; Ecole Technologie Superieure; INRS}},
Abstract = {{In this paper, we develop a novel structure and approach of a pure
   surface Plasmon Polariton (SPP) sensor with fiber Bragg gratings (FBG)
   in gold coated specially designed H-cross-section fiber. We evaluate its
   potential for biological sensing applications of the surrounding
   refractive index (SRI). Pure SPP has almost all its field concentration
   at the metal-dielectric interfaces and hence, it is highly sensitive to
   changes in the sensed medium refractive index. This scheme represents an
   ``in-line{''} optical fiber SPP sensor scheme. Also, it provides larger
   and more flexible sensing area along its flat side. Simulation results
   show that the gold layer thickness essentially influences the
   sensitivity, and the shape of the reflection spectrum. Increasing the
   gold layer thickness decreases its sensitivity and broadens the
   spectrum, increasing the FWHM bandwidth. Results show a maximum
   sensitivity of 230 nm/RIU and maximum figure of merit; defined as the
   ratio of sensitivity to FWHM bandwidth of the reflection spectrum; of
   10952 RIU-1 (Sensitivity = 230 nm/RIU and FWHM = 2.1 x 10(-5) mu m) with
   gold thickness of 10 nm. In conclusion, the proposed sensor is highly
   sensitive and free from any moving parts and can be used as bio-chemical
